terviews with Latino comic book and comic strip authors and artists, including Laura Molina, Frank Espinosa, and Rafael Navarro, complete the study, yielding captivating commentary on the current state of the trade, cultural perceptions, and the intentions of creative individuals who shape their readers in powerful ways.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aComic books, strips, etczUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aHispanic Americans in literature. 0aHispanic AmericansvComic books, strips, etc. 0aMexican AmericansxHistoryy20th century. 0aMexican AmericansxPolitics and government. 0aMexican AmericansxSocial conditions. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / Hispanic American.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292795211423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292795211/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK